Islam can be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
Roger Bootle, Deloitte
Some readers will be attracted by this new book, fans of the author's latest book, " why the French do not like the headscarf " (2006) , an elegant and well documented on an issue that has divided and concerned the country for 15 years and whose effects are still being felt today.
The last book by Mr. Bowen presents a much broader and more ambitious.
Good anthropologist, he does not want to know what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is happening in the country.
He spent many months in mosques, schools and institutes provide now in France this quem. Bozen called " spaces " for the 5m - 6m Muslims.
He knows very well listen and reproduce the debates between teachers and students on the issues that concern them most.
A Muslim must marry in a mosque or at the town hall (or both) ?
The evolution and the rights of homosexuals should be taught to young Muslims?
A Muslim woman can marry a non - Muslim?
A Muslim can use a banking system based on the interests for a loan?
These are practical problems, he says, which are the daily lot, rather than the political dramas concern the media.
The author identifies a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, all unknown to the general public, except perhaps Tariq Ramadan, a Muslim Arab born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how to be a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They do not push the debate until the end.
Lesconservateurs do not believe in the idea of a French or European Islam.
Intellectuals and activists who have been interviewed by Mr. Bowen are generally in agreement with their counterparts lawyers of a Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia that today, are a small part of Muslims in Europe.
M Bowen believes that the values of Muslims and the secularism of the French could be compatible.
But a compromise can be achieved with the efforts of each side.
He wondered how the French politicians (and the intellectual elite guardian if virulent of secularism) are really committed to pluralism.
According to him, Muslims have not been spoiled, compared to Catholics, Protestants and Jews who have also had to make compromises with the secular republicanism.
Rather than a growing pragmatism, he detects a " narrowness of key values ".
Islam can be French? after reading this book, one is tempted to say " yes, but not yet. "
The view of the world's darkest
The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatic than any other place on the planet.
The ice is melting at an alarming rate, taking with it a life that cannot survive elsewhere.
Oil, gas, shipments and new fishing vessels in open waters, with diplomats, lawyers and now writers in their wake.
In " on a thin layer of ice, " Richard Ellis, writer and illustrator, painted a natural history of the symbol of the north, the polar bear.
Knows the history and complicated political of whaling, he described the long tradition of Arctic explorers who were their evidence in hunting polar bears.
The meeting of Admiral Nelson, then courageous aspiring 14 years who had to fight the tip of his musket, is certainly a myth, but the rest is true.
The young cubs, captured while they swam alongside their mother, just killed, were caught and sent to zoos and circuses.
At the beginning of the twentieth century, a show celebrating 75 bears at the same time.
Even today, the dimensions of a zoo are still generally a millionth of the surface necessary for an adult in the climate is rarely mentioned: a polar bear living in Singapore became green because of algae that grew in his thick fur.
Click here for more information!
Mr. Ellis tells the stories of other writers and historians and is often on the threat posed by hunters on the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, the killings continue in Greenland and Canada where hunters by helicopter and the Indians in motoski use fusilsd ' powerful assault to hunt their game.
Ironically, it is in the waters north of these two nations of hunting that ice will be longer.
In his new book, " after the ice ", Alun Anderson, a former editor of New Scientist, offers a clear summary and frightening science of the Arctic and a fascinating glimpse of what may be the future there.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither the atmosphéristes nor oceanographers can tell exactly the speed of change.
This is not for lack of trying.
Late nineteenth and early twentieth, travel pioneers of Fridtjof Nansen gave the first information on the melting of the ice cap.
The submarines in the Cold War were then mapped changes sous - celle - ci.
The surveillance satellites and probes placed on icebergs are a great help, but most of the work is done by men, camping in the cold.
Mr. Anderson the extraordinary world and tiny system dependent on the Arctic ice, formed by the nets of brackish water by freezing.
But the bear mentioned above the microscopic marvels contained in the ice, everything will be lost with the disappearance of summer ice, scheduled between 2013 and 2050.
