The first class Angello Robinson, 19, has made a trip of seven hours by bus to lay a wreath on the grave of a soldier that he had never met.
For him and for the other Marines who made the trip to Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina at Arlington National Cemetery to decorate the graves, this day was devoted to salute the men and women who, one day, were in their place.
In a few months, where we will be sent, we will be in their place, said Robinson about the fallen soldiers.
If it was me, I would like someone to do the same thing for me, that is why I just trying to show respect.
It was one of the 6,000 volunteers to be gathered Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans, in different sections of the cemetery of Arlington Ceremony.
In 1992, Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company to Harrington, Maine, launched the commemoration and others have decided to decorate hundreds of graves in the cemetery of Arlington Ceremony.
Now, to continue a tradition of 18 years, and his wife Karen, each year the journey, stopping in different cities on their way to organize the commemorations in honour of the military and the victims of terrorism.
The Worcester have also founded a non - profit association, Wreaths Across America (wreaths Across America) , which aims to promote the event in all other states.
This year, volunteers have placed more than 16,000 wreaths on the graves of the Arlington, around the Pentagon, on the graves of the cemetery Fayetteville National Cemetery enArkansas, in the Battery Park in New York City and on the site of the memorial to the victims of United Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second consecutive year, the Walmart Foundation has given more than $150,000 to buy and carry the crowns.
Charleen Hunt, 70, of Westminster, said that she had made the trip to Arlington in honour of her husband, a career soldier died.
While her husband is not buried at Arlington, Hunt said that for her, it was a way to thank those who had sacrificed.
It is a small gesture that civilians can do to support our troops, she said.
It is like visiting a family tomb.
In several layers of warm clothing, volunteers walked between the lawns and hills tracts of the cemetery.
The volunteers have chosen ancient tombs, dating from the First and Second World war, as well as the Vietnam War, because they are not often visited the new graves, said the organizers.
The mood was optimistic, while children played and couples were held by the hand, wearing the crowns of fresh pine on the graves.
Each crown round had a dark green colour, with a small red butterfly knot on the top.
Nearby, was silent on the Section 60, where most of the veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried.
The United Service Organizations has given 1,000 crowns to decorate the section but the dark mood of the current wars filled the area.
People without hiding, others praying and families and friends back in the cold air.
Some read aloud the names engraved in stone while others looked to see small black and white information cards in the wetland for those whose tomb had not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers in tears, on the grave of her son.
It is part of Zanesfield, Ohio and had led eight hours to come to collect on the grave of Marine Sergeant GunneryDavid Shane Spicer, died in combat in July.
No one should ever forget thanks to what we are free ... my son has paid for it, " she said.
" long after I am gone, I want someone to remember him. "
