The only one that had set an auction has lost.
Two American companies have won contracts for the fields auctioned in June.
The low representation of American oil giants in the opening of the oil sector in Iraq has surprised analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors, after six years of war, and instead of American companies, are of Asian and European companies are leading the way, said Ruba Husari, editor of the forum Iraq Oil Forum, a site of information on the Internet.
It will take a long time before another offer is made in Iraq.
The concerns about security, corroborated by massive coordinated bombings, Tuesday, and political instability, while the US military troops withdraw have slowed the American oil companies, preventing them from entering with more force in Iraq, which has the third largest oil reserve in the world, say analysts.
American companies were, in some cases, disadvantaged because of their rivals, especially the Chinese and other energy companies controlled by a government, whose labour costs were significantly lower and who were more willing to take risks because they had not accountable to shareholders.
Exxon - Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only companies to obtain contracts with the department.
The most important American companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which have maintained strong links with the Iraqi Ministry of Oil and brought their technical advice, are left empty - handed.
The Russian company Lukoil and Gazprom were the two main shareholders in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The Chinese National Petroleum Corp., owned by the state, has more on contracts that other companies and is left with significant holdings in contracts for two main fields.
We all know that China is becoming a major economy, as well as a technological power, said Assam Jihad, spokesman of the Ministry of Oil.
We are confident that the Chinese society will be on an equal footing with its competitors and achieve its commitments in Iraq.
The pre - selected companies to submit auction bid which were then compared to the price per barrel that the department agreed to pay to motivate the production above current levels for each field.
One of the main organizers of al-Qaeda have been killed in Pakistan
It seems that an American missile, which hit along the border with Afghanistan has killed one of the organizers of the operations of al-Qaeda, this week, said Friday the U. S. authorities of counter - intelligence.
If the information is confirmed, it would be the second deadly attack against a terrorist leaders this fall.
Saleh al-Somali was one of two Arab men suspected to have been killed by a pair of missiles launched in their car, Tuesday, near the city of Miran Shah, in the province of North Waziristan, according to US and Pakistani authorities in the region.
Local authorities have said that the missiles were fired by a pilotless aircraft of the type used by the CIA, inside the lawless tribal border of Pakistan.
They were driving a white car, heading towards the Afghan border, when the car was hit, said a member of the secret services Pakistani civilians, speaking by telephone from Miran Shah.
The authorities have said that the local militant suspects rushed to place and quickly confiscated what remained of " body completely.
It was completely impossible to local authorities to verify the identity of the victims, but the two U. S. counter - terrorism officials have given unspecified evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somali was described as one of the organizers of military officials who ran the al-Qaeda terrorist group outside the Afghanistan - Pakistan region.
Its role was to organize conspiracies in the world, " said one of the authorities who requested anonymity, citing the sensitive nature of the air strikes inside Pakistani territory.
Given its central role, this included probably conspiracies of attacks against the United States and Europe.
It followed the strategic guidance of the leaders of al-Qaeda and has translated into action plans for possible terrorist attacks.
A second representative of the American authority said that Somali had increased rapidly in the ranks of al-Qaida's and had very good relations with other extremist groups in the region.
It is not known to the general public, but this does not diminish the threat it poses for us and our allies, " said the second official representative.
If his death is confirmed, would be the second major figure of al-Qaeda or the Taliban leader killed since September, when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, leader of a faction of militants in the tribal belt, as well as three other operators.
The pace of attacks carried out by CIA drones has declined since the summer, about six transactions per month to two, according to the figures by the Long War Journal, a Web site tempered by a non - profit group.
This decline is perhaps due to improved tactics of terrorist groups that have progressed to reduce their vulnerability while killing also ruthlessly suspected informants, says the site.
The UN special envoy to Kabul withdrew
The UN special envoy in Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said Friday that he would resign from his post in March, at the end of a tumultuous tenure marred by allegations of corruption during the presidential elections supported by the United Nations.
The departure comes as the Obama administration decided to send 30,000 additional troops in Afghanistan.
The UN envoy said that he supported the increase, but he expressed concern about the timetable for a withdrawal of US troops that would begin in 18 months and that would force the other NATO governments to withdraw their forces.
We need to accelerate the development of our security forces in Afghanistan, send the right signal to Afghans and remind them that they can have confidence in the international community, " Eide said in a telephone interview from Kabul.
Our commitment must be long - term.
The Norwegian diplomat has also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international staff helping the political transition in Afghanistan.
The increase must be copied by civilians, he said.
Eide said that he did not resign but that it would honour the commitment that he made to his family in March, will spend two years in Kabul.
He said he wanted to prevent the United Nations.
The Secretary - General Ban Ki - moon now knows that he has time to find a replacement.
I simply said that it was better to start looking for my replacement, said Eide.
When I came here, there was a gap of two months between the departure of my predecessor and my arrival.
According to the representatives of the UN, Ban has already begun to seek a replacement.
The representatives say that the name of Staffan di Mistura has been cited; it is a citizen Italo - Swiss recently chaired a UN mission in Baghdad and Jean - Marie Guéhenno, a Frenchman who has previously led the peacekeeping operations of the United Nations.
The reputation of Eide in Afghanistan has been put to the test after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, was accused in September, President Hamid Karzai during the presidential elections and to conceal evidence of massive electoral fraud.
Eide denied these allegations, but he said that the accusations of Galbraith -- who was thanked -- " have damaged the mission because there was already a good dose of scepticism as regards the international observation of the elections ".
Eide said he had proposed the appointment of a civilian representative to coordinate the rescue of American forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged the UN to allow his successor to hire more staff from the United States and other Western countries that it is attributed to the mission in Afghanistan, saying that this would give them more confidence about how their money is spent.
Eide has expressed his frustration about the limits of its powers in Afghanistan, saying that the heavy regulation of hiring UN hindered its ability to bring new talent.
The rules are such that I was unable to recruit one person since May, he said.
It is catastrophic and it cannot last.
Gates: Iran must undergo additional sanctions
The Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates said Friday that world powers would soon impose " significant additional sanctions " on Iran because of its inability to engage in talks on the nuclear ambitions.
Gates, speaking before a crowd of 300 American soldiers in northern Iraq, during a visit to a week in war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq, has the possibility of military action against the Islamic Republic.
There is no good option in Iran, he said, in response to the question of a soldier on the possibility of such an outcome.
One of the things that strikes me the most is that if I learned one thing in Iraq over the past six years, it is the unpredictability inherent in the war.
The Obama administration considers a set of sanctions against the military and political elite in Iran, but Gates has indicated that some of these sanctions could also affect the Iranians in the street.
He said that " a package of incentives and punishments " might be needed to persuade the Iranian government that it would in fact less good security with nuclear weapons " because " his people would suffer greatly of these sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement from the White House spokesman, Robert Gibbs, the administration has joined the European leaders in warning that Iran will face consequences " probable " if it does not bring its nuclear program in full compliance with the UN Security Council and its supervisory body, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) .
Iran continues to say that he wants to develop its nuclear experience only in a peaceful purposes.
In the Geneva talks on October 1, he indicated that it would resume dialogue on the reduction of its nuclear programme and agreed to give up a significant part of its stockpile of enriched uranium in exchange for fuel desperately needed for a medical research reactor.
The administration has prompted such an agreement, way to build confidence on both sides and to save time for negotiations.
Since then, Iran appears to be attempts - in part, experts say, because the Iranian leadership is divided on whether or not to engage with the United States.
Frankly, I think, the stiffening of Iran with some of the proposals of the international community to which they had given their agreement in early October, has led the international community, including the Russians and the Chinese, to join what they had not considered, in terms of significant additional sanctions against the Iranians, said Gates.
President Obama has set a December 31 deadline for Iran to respond to the proposals, before it turned to other options, including the continuation of what Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called " increased sanctions ".
In a statement Thursday in New York, the mission of Iran to the United Nations has denounced what it called " baseless allegations " of some members of the Security Council on the nuclear activities of Iran and said it was agreed to continue talks with the United States and five other major world powers, " in order to obtain a satisfactory solution in the long term ".
Gates, who was to return to Washington late Friday, met in the morning, the Iraqi Prime Minister, Nouri al-Maliki, before flying to the oil rich region of Kurdish derencontrer Heads of troops in Kirkuk, Kurdish and Irbil.
Tensions persist between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq, particularly on the borders, property rights and the sharing of revenues.
Gates has urged both sides to reduce the potential conflict in order to avoid any delays of US plans to reduce the number of American troops, 115 000 to 50 000 before the end of August.
Gates also wants to calm the anxiety of Kurds concerning the withdrawal pending. The American authorities have quoted Gates saying to Massoud Barzani, president of the Kurdistan regional government: " We will preserve your security, prosperity and your autonomy within a unified Iraq. "
We will not abandon you. "
In China, a change of direction
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by the propaganda poster preaching, " the Mother Earth is too tired to accommodate more children " and " a baby, it is a grave in more ".
They have learned the lesson that the authorities of the Government of Shanghai, alarmed by the lack of birth rate of their city and the ageing of the population, have radically changed direction this summer and began to encourage young couples to have more than one child; their reaction was instant and firm: never.
We have already given all our time and energy to one child.
There is no second, said Wang, 31, director of human resources and has a son of 8 months.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one - child policy in China, creating two generations of children unique notoriously with good cheeks and spoiled, dubbed the " little emperors ", a crisis of the population threatens the country.
According to the UN, the average birth rate fell from 1.8 children per couple compared to six when the policy was implemented.
The distribution of the population, while it is expected that the number of residents aged 60 and over will explode, 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050. This figure is well above the global average of about 20 percent.
This imbalance is even worse in the rich coastal cities with a highly educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for almost 22 percent of the population of residents registered in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission (Commission of the Shanghai Municipal Population and family Planning) said that the fertile couples to have babies in order " to help reduce the proportion of the aging population and to prevent a lack of manpower in the future ".
Shanghai is on the verge of becoming " too old - but not as rich, however - that the developed countries such as Japan and Sweden, " she said.
A gradual reduction
Written in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one - child policy is to this day, without doubt, the most controversial requirement introduced by the communist government.
Couples who violate this policy may have to pay huge fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and suffer discrimination in the workplace.
The Chinese authorities have attributed to the police on duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while lawyers for human rights have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some representatives of the authority have forced pregnant women a second child to have abortions.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to a ratio of boys to girls abnormally high.
In recent years, the authorities of the population have gradually softened their position on the one - child policy.
In 2004, they have given more exceptions to the rule -- including for residents of cities, members of ethnic minorities and the cases in which the man and the woman are already children -- and in 2007, they have softened much of their slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research (Institute of Population Research at Peking University, said that the authorities of the central government have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one partner is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, the posters encouraging families to have only one child have been replaced by copies of regulations retailer who has the right to have a second child and how to apply for authorization.
The city government has dispatched family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples at home, and slipping leaflets under their door.
He has also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the head of family planning, the response has been disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for records of couples wanting a second child after the launch of the campaign, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115 million inhabitants, for example, is four to five requests per month.
Officials in Shanghai, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city, in 2010, is still expected to be only about 165 000 -- slightly higher in 2009 but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, Head of the Committee of family planning in the Caolu of Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to provide their first child, she said.
Yang, 27 years and his wife, Liu, 26, said they would love to have two children and that they are legally allowed.
But like many Chinese, they have only the minimum health insurance and life assurance given by the government.
Without a social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
The Western mistakenly see that the one - child policy is a matter of rights, " said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
It is true, we are fortunate to have more than one child.
But the problem is not only the law.
It is money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their reluctance.
Wang, Head of human resources, said she wanted a single child because it itself. " We were the centre of the family and had used that everyone cares. "
We do not have the habit of taking care of someone else and we really do not want to take care of others. "
Chen Zijian, 42 years and owner of a translation company said more bluntly.
For couples working at two, middle class, which reduce the birth rate, he says, he must be selfish pourbien succeed.
The people of 20 or 30 years have grown up watching their parents struggle in the early days of the China capitalist and do not want to have themselves this way of life, " he says.
Even one child takes a lot of time with his parents, he says.
A mother must abandon at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the problems of space -- " You must change your apartment " -- and planning -- " When your child has only 9 months, you need to write his CV for a place in the best mother. "
Most of his friends are willing to this experience once, said Chen, but not two.
Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living, " he says.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
The group of the United Nations plans for reducing emissions
The climate conference, sponsored by the United Nations -- characterized so far by disorganized and mutual recriminations is back in the spotlight Friday, due to the publication of a document outlining the ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations supporting most of the burden in the coming years.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, said the remaining obstacles, as he has informed the path to take.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations that lack of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Prepared by a special working group of the United Nations, the text does not say how rich countries would give the poor to withstand global warming, short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how the developed economies and the emerging economies could reduce their production of carbon and what would be the upper limit of the increase in global temperature that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility in the process, said John Coequyt, Representative of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has written six pages of the document, studied a text of 180 pages to focus on what has described the Secretary - General on climate change, Yvo de Boer, as " the full picture ".
It shows the guidelines of a possible agreement in which the industrial nations collectively reduce their emissions in 2020, from 25 to 45 percent compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, during the same period, reduce by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched negotiations, Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help the poorest countries to adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercation occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, the US Representative to the negotiating climate has rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, in comparison with the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration becomes harder to China that the Bush administration has been two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions of the major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text does not enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs, He Yafei has said that the US chief negotiator, lacked " common sense ", was " extremely irresponsible " for having said earlier in the week that the US would not help financially China to combat global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of major world powers involved, defects are both within the third and between the industrial world and the emerging economies.
The current battle is more concerned with the rescue of individual economies that the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States on their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen of the most influential scientific imperatives to act more boldly.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate of Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of the reduction of greenhouse gases, even if the vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make the major emitters accountable for their actions.
It really is a game in which has developed a new economic hegemony, said Ulate, who is also advising on the climate for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they would continue to put pressure for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the major participants say that the negotiations will lead to a minimum, a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States which brings together 43 members, has drafted a proposal for a treaty of 24 pages, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge - Metzger, head of the unit of the European Commission, said that the action of small island states has " put political pressure on the political process in part by what they are now unified and they ask to emerging economies such as China and India, to act.
The debates have become a matter of urgency, while delegates focused on the fact that they should solve most of the problems pending before the heads of government come to an agreement.
High - level officials such as the Indian environment Minister, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister descended from their plane and rushed into the building of the Bella Center to attend meetings and conferences of information, in order to make claims that will be considered during the course of the following week.
The real image of the gathering -- in which 13,000 people entering and exiting the Palais des Congrès every day -- activists guitar players are nocturnal entertainment mocking countries which they betray and that proposals are prepared and distributed on paper rather than by emails -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is increasing: almost all key ministers are here and not later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the big, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy of Conservation International.
Lorries arrive.
In Britain, the first train to 225 km/h will redefine the syndrome Monday
5h13, Monday morning, a whistle night to signal the start of a train that will mark a revolution of transport in Britain.
The first high - speed commuter train in the country will reach 225 km/h, of Ashford, in Kent, to London St Pancras, covering the 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Transport Minister, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes aboard the first commuter train Javelin outside London.
He hoped that the new service will allow Britain to integrate an international network of fast trains and reliable and will link the large conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The small holes lost will become thriving suburbs, business travel will be much less long and the passage of the plane and the car to the train will reduce national emissions of carbon while reducing congestion on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties adhering to this project.
But the ten billion pounds needed to build a new rail network, the battle of planning inevitable and fears of risks to the environment may dampen the high - speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2) , a company established in January for the government to conduct a feasibility report, will make his report to Lord Adonis on 30 December.
This will allow him to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next stage for the high - speed network.
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be drawn in the five metres of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment can be controversial.
In the campaign, the plan will be drawn up to 25 metres of the final itinerary.
It is also expected that HS2 presents three options for a high - speed network, to the north.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
The preferred options are put forward in a configuration for which a high - speed line will go to the West Midlands.
The line will split into two at or near Birmingham, with a branch from the west Pennines àManchester and Scotland and another to the northeast, Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line through Scotland.
" It seems that this will be the best option of performance said a professional of rail.
When this is completed, the journey time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first part, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to an hour now.
The proposals will allow the train to travel 400km/h, making the UK network the fastest in the world.
The original route is designed to allow trains to 400m in length and can carry 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can operate on a line London - Birmingham.
A terminal that can accommodate 20,000 passengers per hour would be necessary.
Given the constraints of space, it is anticipated that an existing station will be expanded to receive the high - speed network.
The rail industry experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he feels that the project must be put in place, but public consultations longer and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be taken before a general election.
Even if it launches the machine, the network will be built by.
The trains will be forced to drive out of high - speed lines on the existing track north of Birmingham, journey times between London and Scotland more than three hours.
This seems to be the best to ensure a way of trains, a reference point for the revolution.
