USA: a sign of sarcophagus belonged to Zola awarded $1.5 million
A panel of Roman sarcophagus belonged to the French writer Emile Zola was awarded Thursday $1.5 million, well above its estimate, announced the art dealer Sotheby's.
This sign before two metres long on 63 cm high, dating from the third century A. D., was estimated at between 150,000 and 250,000 dollars.
The marble " representing four scenes in a sophisticated architectural decor, surrounded by satyres and bacchantes, is a rare, there are four or five in the world, " explained to AFP Tuesday Florent Heintz, vice - president of the auction of art of the ancient Roman and Egyptian in Sotheby's.
It was sold a hundred lots.
The sale is still ongoing but this lot is certainly the one on which buyers have the most excellent so far, told AFP a Sotheby's spokesman, Dan Abernethy.
The discovery of the acquisition of the marble by Emile Zola back in a few days.
The panel has remained almost 300 years in Rome in the famous collection of the family, then became successively in the French actress Cécile Sorel, who had made an element of his bathtub in her Parisian mansion, and Paul Reynaud, Minister under the Third Republic in France and President of the Council before the accession to power of Marshal Pétain.
Still a grey area of fifty years.
In searching the database of the Louvre Museum, Florent Heintz has discovered that this was part of a " succession Emile Zola " opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of " Thérèse Raquin " and " Rougon - Macquart ".
Departure of Zelaya of Honduras to Mexico
Mexico has seen Thursday that the conditions were not right for the transfer on its territory of the deposed president of Honduras, Manuel Zelaya, who was denied a safe conduct by the government.
For the moment, after a telephone conversation in the night with President Zelaya, everything seems to indicate that the possibility of achieving this transfer are not met, " said the Mexican Foreign Minister Patricia Espinosa.
Arrived Wednesday in El Salvador to restore Mr Zelaya, the Mexican government plane returned to its place of origin, according to a source of the General Directorate of Migration.
The government wanted to force Mr Zelaya to " resign " and to seek political asylum abroad to give him a pass.
But the president refused, because he wanted to go to Mexico as a sitting head of state invited.
The government " has been a new failure in that I renounced my burden (...) , they wanted me to resign, " said Mr Zelaya Radio Globo, on which it is often since the beginning of the political crisis that has lasted for five months in the countries of Central America.
I can stay here ten years here I have my guitar, added by playing a few agreements president, refugee at the Brazilian embassy in Tegucigalpa for two and a half months.
The Embassy of Mexico has submitted an application of safe conduct, but unfortunately we cannot accept it because it contains no asylum application, said Wednesday the Minister of the Interior of the rebel government, Oscar Raul Matute, HRN radio.
I do not seek asylum in any country, said Manuel Zelaya in an interview with the channel Telesur, based in Caracas.
A possible departure of Honduras will do as president of the Honduran people, he said.
Rumours of departure of Mr Zelaya had mobilized Wednesday, supporters of the deposed president, who came to gather around the embassy of Brazil, where the military have strengthened their seat.
The Brazilian Foreign Minister, Celso Amorim, has criticised the government's position.
This demonstrates the marginal nature of this government to international standards, he said.
Zelaya, who was close to the socialist President Hugo Chavez, was ousted on June 28, the day he had organized a popular consultation to prepare his re - election, against the advice of the Supreme Court, military and Congress.
Exile in Costa Rica, it was returned by surprise on 21 September and took refuge at the Embassy of Brazil.
If he leaves, he will be arrested for the offence of " high treason " which accuses justice, according to the government.
The President Roberto Micheletti has managed to hold a presidential election on 29 November to replace Mr Zelaya.
Porfirio Lobo was elected during the controversial recognized by the United States but disputed by Latin American countries such as Venezuela, Argentina or Brazil.
Three days later, the Congress voted overwhelmingly against the return of Mr Zelaya to power until the end of his term on 27 January.
