A few hundred supporters of the Cuban authorities have shouted down Thursday wives of political prisoners gathered in Havana for the World Day of human rights, and prevented another event for which a dozen dissidents were arrested.
40 " Ladies in White, wives or relatives of political prisoners, were conspuées in the street by supporters of the government of Raul Castro as they walked towards the centre of the capital to demand the release of political prisoners, has been a journalist of the AFP.
Down the Yankees! , " mercenaries! ", " the street belongs to the revolutionary! ", " Long live Fidel and Raul! ", raised fist, supporters of power.
They were escorted by plainclothes officers came " ensure their protection. "
The day before, a similar event was held against the " Ladies in White " in Havana, with no injuries or arrests.
But in the havanais of Vedado, a dozen dissidents who were to demonstrate Thursday for the International Day of human rights have been arrested by plainclothes police officers, a journalist of the AFP.
The police have been driving force in civilian vehicles dissidents who have been vilified by supporters of the government, according to the journalist.
The arrests of dissidents in similar circumstances usually last only a few hours.
Recipients of the 2005 Sakharov Prize of the European Parliament, the " Ladies in White " had organized a march to demand the release of all political prisoners, " the number of 200 according to the dissent, " said one of their leaders, Laura Pollan, whose husband Hector Maceda is serving a sentence of 20 years in prison.
Mr Maceda is part of the group of 75 Cuban dissidents arrested in March 2003, of which 53 are in prison.
The Cuban authorities consider opponents as " mercenaries " or " agents " in the pay of their enemy, the United States.
Rare, Cuban television reported the event on Thursday of pro - government activists against " counter - revolutionaries ".
Cuba, led by a single party, the Communist Party, is regularly accused by NGOs European or American rights and freedoms, including freedom of expression.
