The Turkish justice dissolved the pro - Kurdish party, decision consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled Friday the dissolution of the main pro - Kurdish party in the country, a decision that was immediately followed by expressions of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south - east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which is to reach out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a " home of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity, " said to the press the president of the Court Hasim Kiliç, after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously of the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to make the dissolution, said Mr Kiliç, adding that 37 of party officials, including its president Ahmet Türk and Tugluk, are banned from politics for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Mrs Tugluk and the confiscation of the assets of the party.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (550) .
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that members would leave Parliament rather than sit as members without label.
The decision follows a process launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP to obey " directives " of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) , considered a terrorist organisation by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political wing of the PKK rebels.
The party is, however, that there was " no organic links " with the PKK but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with him.
The verdict of the Court comes as the government is to reach out to the Kurdish community in proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, to try to shrink the support of Kurds and put an end to the conflict.
The leaders of the DTP had said that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in the southeast, where many demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
After the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP in Diyarbakir, the largest city in the southeast majority of Kurds.
The police fired tear gas and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails and stones, with slingshots.
About 100 people demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said that the decision of Justice would " deepen the despair. "
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdish) by banning a party, " he said to the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This solves nothing, " said Minister of Energy Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total of democratic openness launched by the government, " said political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, " he added.
On Thursday, the PKK has claimed an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in the north of Turkey, one of the most deadly in recent months.
The new " Silicon - valley "
For a long time she had the reputation of city secret, off - limits to visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the 10 districts of Moscow, was under the Soviet regime, a place of secret weapons, under strict supervision.
Today, with its 216 000 inhabitants to 37 km from the centre of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the " Silicon Valley ".
Important sites of production and research of micro - and nanoelectronics.
In September 2008 representatives of Zelenograd have established links with Riedberg, place of science - with academic institutions and companies in the centre of Frankfurt (FIZ) .
There were meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg have signed a " memorandum of close collaboration ".
The signatories were the Deputy mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and the prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz section head project for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of the FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific Exchange
It is a scientific exchange.
But also of economic relations.
It will allow the companies to enter the Russian market in full expansion.
Has the Russian scientific societies seeking contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of research institutes and companies Soviet famous.
There is the Institute of Electrical Engineering from Moscow, the major firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja - Elektronika.
The municipality was founded in 1958 as " socialist planned city " for research.
Zelenograd (literal translation " green City ") gets its name from the forested hills in the heart of which research centres are located.
The project S21: a brake for Stuttgart
We cannot place high enough the magnitude of the project Stuttgart 21.
To its supporters it is nothing less than " new heart of Europe ".
If is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a massive construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden - Württemberg, in a chaos of yards for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 is born of the spirit of the 1980s.
The stations, with tracks which ended in town, had a reputation at the time to be the relics of the technique of the 19th century that were effect of brake shoe modern rail traffic because it was once a lot of time to get from the back to the front.
Arrival, stopping short, departure - that is what needs to be done.
That is why the head of the line must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And Stuttgart also: a station of trains, which is about halfway on the trans - European rail between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava where the slogan " heart of Europe ".
The project S21 will really start, although the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners have recognized that the cost to bury the station in the capitals of Hesse and Bavaria, was exorbitant.
Indeed, the head of line stations no longer pose real problems of entry and exit since there are modern trains, reversible with railcars and voiture - pilote at both ends.
However, it is now the achievement of Stuttgart 21 alongside the new line of the inter - city Ulm.
The regional and local prevailed.
The railway company is in part because it is the taxpayer who paid the cost of the risks of the largest infrastructure project of the Federal Republic and not the public company.
From the point of view of this project is relatively well justified.
There is an urban area - according to the computer - generated graphics planners - will be very green.
For the system of rail transport the S21 is harmful.
The station and the enlargement of the section are designed for trafficking is - and this is typical of the 1980s - a huge growth.
At the time there was no competition from cheap flights.
The policy of modern traffic should first focus on strengthening the traffic of goods transport by rail is much more environmentally friendly than by truck on the road.
But the new route, with its inclinations, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious indirectly affects many other rail projects.
For example, six billion euros will be swallowed up in the draft of the
It is the official figure.
Experts believe that ten to 15 billion are more realistic.
One thing is sure, in the next decade will this money for other junction and congestion in the network.
The list of the Department of Transport in 60 major projects.
One of the most important is the enlargement of the section across the Rhine Valley of 180 kilometres.
Since 1987 the line is built.
It would be really urgent support here to build on the fungus.
But the project is a braking.
The itinerary of the Rhine Valley is becoming the bottleneck of international freight traffic, and this in the heart of Europe.
