US banks repay the aid
The big American banks, very affected by the crisis, shedding their ties to the state.
The Bank of America announced Wednesday that it had fully repaid to the Treasury $45 billion (more than 30 billion Euros) , corresponding to the aid granted in the framework of the rescue plan.
The American television channel CNBC reported in a story that Citigroup was also planning to repay the aid received.
The banking institutions seek to get rid of restrictions, which accompanied the acceptance of the money, such as limiting bonuses awarded to the leader and the regulation of higher costs.
The Bank of Americaa launched a capital increase by the sale of securities to investors who reported $19 billion of fresh money.
The rest of the money comes from the coffers of the bank are met through the sale of several branches of other sectors.
Last Wednesday night, Kenneth Lewis, the Director General of the Bank of America held specifically to thank the American taxpayers: the injection of capital has significantly helped to overcome a difficult period.
The bank had assumed its capacity by buying the investment bank Merrill Lynch at the height of the financial turmoil.
The Citigroup also plans to get money on the financial markets to free themselves from the guardianship of the state.
The U. S. bank could launch as early as Thursday a capital increase of $20 billion, reported the CNBC citing the banking community.
The spokesman for Citigroup did not wish to comment on this information.
In June the banks Goldman Sachs, JP Morgan Chase and Morgan Stanley had repaid the public funds they had received.
