Acciona dispute its first highway in Australia to Hochtief and Bouygues
Acciona is fighting for his first motorway concession in Australia, market on which it is already working as a business manager of energy and water.
The site at stake is a tunnel estimated at 700 million Australian dollars (about 1 million euros) .
The French company Bouygues and the German company Hochtief are its rivals.
A tunnel of 5 kilometres long in the Australian city of Brisbane, on the East Coast, such is the option to allow Acciona to settle in the country as a company of public works and highways.
The mayor of the city wants to have by the end of 2014.
Having chosen the public/private partnership (PPP for its initials in English) to complete the project, in the framework of a business plan under the tutelage of Erns& Young, the local administration already has a list of finalists who will be responsible for the construction and operation of the toll.
Pending the presentation of their bids in May, the planned investment amounts to 1 700 million Australian dollars (about 1 million euros) and in the last phase three consortia, with a significant presence of European manufacturers.
The group called Transcity is led by Acciona, only Spanish company in smooth, and his associates are MDBs and Ghella.
The first is one of the largest manufacturers, while the second, in Italy, is one of the largest European specialists to work underground.
Against the team of Acciona, the consortium Northern Direct, with the presence of the British firm Laing O'Rourke, manager of the Australian infrastructure and the French manufacturer group Bouygues.
The third and final consortium that has passed the test is LBRJV, whose capital is shared between the Australian Leighton (a subsidiary of the German builder Hochtief, which has in turn the participation of GBA) , another local company, Baulderstone (property of the German group Bilfinger Berger) and the Welsh company specializing in public works, Razel.
The Australian market infrastructure promises of major projects and privatisation, but there is a great difficulty, if not through the acquisition of a local construction company.
A strategy that followed the companies Hochtief and Bilfinger, already mentioned, in addition to their Asian, and which is still a step not validated for the Spanish giants of the sector.
GBA is just to win a place on the market by its 30% stake in Hochtief, owner of Leighton.
Active millionaires
Acciona on a geographical area of the utmost importance for the sector, on which it already has a large presence through its energy supplier and activity in the sector.
Among other assets, it has the largest wind farm, Waubra (192 MW) in Victoria, and leads the group of companies responsible for building and managing the dessalinisateur of Adelaide, with a budget of 700 million.
It now intends to consolidate these two areas and take advantage of synergies to enter the markets of the construction and management of infrastructure.
The underground road toll, promoted by the Office of the infrastructure of the city of Brisbane and the Northern Link (north) , is called upon to link the western peripheral route to Kelvin Grove (see map) , by 4 kilometres of tunnel. It is the largest project to reduce traffic congestion in Brisbane.
The timetable set by the administration said that the auction will take place during the summer of 2010 and that the work will begin in December of next year.
Despite the fact that the toll road will be open to traffic at the end of 2014, it is not anticipated that the site is completed before 2016.
The tunnel began to be developed in 2005.
It will include two tracks, an electronic toll system and a complex ventilation system.
The Queensland Government will provide 500 million Australian dollars (308 million euros) for its funding.
